{
  "doc_id": "46368",
  "text": "An alternative approach to empirical bioclimatic relationships is to define physiological tolerances in terms of adaptations allowing plants to tolerate climatic constraints [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . For example, [CITATION_4] proposed functional trade-offs between growth, maintenance and reproduction as a mechanism for explaining species survival and coexistence in plant communities. Given finite resources, individual plant species must \"choose\" between growing fast or growing old, producing large or numerous seeds, or investing their carbon into storage or anti-predatory traits [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . For this reason trade-offs are fundamental to the concept of plant growth strategies. Because of these functional trade-offs in resource allocation and growth strategies, similar climatic constraints have led to the evolution of similar plant forms and functions independent of phylogenetic taxonomy (Schimper, 1898) .",
